Section 2 : Overview¶

In this project we aim to predict and classify whether a passenger survived the Titanic disaster, using the dataset -Titanic - Machine Learning from Disaster from Kaggle.

We will use a Logistic Regression model to perform our predictions. Our workflow includes data exploration, processing of the data, statistical analyses, training the model, and evaluating its performance.

# extracting Name
train_df['Title'] = train_df['Name'].str.extract(r' ([A-Za-z]+)\.', expand=False)

# merging rare titles
train_df['Title'] = train_df['Title'].replace([
    'Lady', 'Countess', 'Capt', 'Col', 'Don', 'Dr', 'Major',
    'Rev', 'Sir', 'Jonkheer', 'Dona'], 'Rare')

train_df['Title'] = train_df['Title'].replace(['Mlle', 'Ms'], 'Miss')
train_df['Title'] = train_df['Title'].replace('Mme', 'Mrs')

# deleting Name
train_df.drop('Name', axis=1, inplace=True)

Section 9.1 : Checking how to fill in 'Age' missing values using Bootstrapping¶

Since the Age factor played a crucial role in surviving in the titanic, and we have seen how important it is it the data visualization, we will fill the missing values in that column.

To evaluate the impact of different imputation strategies for missing values in the 'Age' feature, we tested both mean and median. We used a KNN classifier to compare the performance of both strategies on the validation set since KNN is sensitive to the scale and distribution of features and it is useful for assessing the effect of the filled values.

Using median:

In [29]:
#Bootstraping valitation using KNN
def bootstrap_validation_knn(X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, n_iterations=100, random_state=42):
    np.random.seed(random_state)
    acc_scores = []
    prec_scores = []
    rec_scores = []
    f1_scores = []

    model = KNeighborsClassifier()

    for _ in range(n_iterations):
        X_bs, y_bs = resample(X_train, y_train)
        model.fit(X_bs, y_bs)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_val)

        acc_scores.append(accuracy_score(y_val, y_pred))
        prec_scores.append(precision_score(y_val, y_pred))
        rec_scores.append(recall_score(y_val, y_pred))
        f1_scores.append(f1_score(y_val, y_pred))

    return {
        "accuracy_scores": acc_scores,
        "precision_scores": prec_scores,
        "recall_scores": rec_scores,
        "f1_scores": f1_scores,
        "mean_accuracy": np.mean(acc_scores),
        "std_accuracy": np.std(acc_scores),
        "mean_error": 1 - np.mean(acc_scores),
        "mean_precision": np.mean(prec_scores),
        "mean_recall": np.mean(rec_scores),
        "mean_f1": np.mean(f1_scores)
    }


bootstrap_knn_result = bootstrap_validation_knn(X_train1, y_train1, X_val1, y_val1)

print(f"Mean Accuracy:     {bootstrap_knn_result['mean_accuracy']:.2%}")
print(f"Standard Deviation:{bootstrap_knn_result['std_accuracy']:.2%}")
print(f"Error Rate:        {bootstrap_knn_result['mean_error']:.2%}")
print(f"Precision:         {bootstrap_knn_result['mean_precision']:.2%}")
print(f"Recall:            {bootstrap_knn_result['mean_recall']:.2%}")
print(f"F1 Score:          {bootstrap_knn_result['mean_f1']:.2%}")

Mean Accuracy:     77.57%
Standard Deviation:2.57%
Error Rate:        22.43%
Precision:         71.47%
Recall:            69.24%
F1 Score:          70.21%

Section 10 : Feature selection¶

Since our features are limited, we will first try and use backward feature selection (using CV with recursive feature elimination).

The optimal model performance was achieved using just three features: Sex, Pclass, and Age. The R² score peaked at 3 features and adding more did not improve the results.

Since Hybrid Feature Selection combines the strengths of both forward and backward methods we will try it as well. This might lead to a more accurate model.

Section 11 : Model Building (Baseline Validation Performance)¶

Before going further, we had like to see how various different models perform with default parameters. We tried the following models using bootstrapping to get a baseline. With a validation set basline, we can see how much tuning improves each of the models. Just because a model has a high basline on this validation set doesn't mean that it will actually do better on the eventual test set but it will help us choose the models for our ensembles.

In [42]:
def bootstrap_validation_score(model, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, n_iterations=100, random_state=42):
    accuracy_scores = []
    precision_scores = []
    recall_scores = []
    f1_scores = []
    confusion_matrices = []
    train_accuracy_scores = []
    train_losses = []
    val_losses = []

    for i in range(n_iterations):
        X_bs, y_bs = resample(X_train, y_train, random_state=random_state + i)
        model.fit(X_bs, y_bs)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_val)

        accuracy_scores.append(accuracy_score(y_val, y_pred))
        precision_scores.append(precision_score(y_val, y_pred))
        recall_scores.append(recall_score(y_val, y_pred))
        f1_scores.append(f1_score(y_val, y_pred))

        y_pred_train = model.predict(X_bs)
        train_accuracy_scores.append(accuracy_score(y_bs, y_pred_train))

        cm = confusion_matrix(y_val, y_pred)
        confusion_matrices.append(cm)

        if hasattr(model, "predict_proba"):
            y_proba_val = model.predict_proba(X_val)
            y_proba_train = model.predict_proba(X_bs)
            val_losses.append(log_loss(y_val, y_proba_val))
            train_losses.append(log_loss(y_bs, y_proba_train))
        else:
            val_losses.append(np.nan)
            train_losses.append(np.nan)

    mean_cm = np.round(np.mean(confusion_matrices, axis=0)).astype(int)
    cm_df = pd.DataFrame(mean_cm,
                         index=["Actual 0", "Actual 1"],
                         columns=["Predicted 0", "Predicted 1"])

    return {
        "mean_val_accuracy": round(np.mean(accuracy_scores), 4),
        "mean_train_accuracy": round(np.mean(train_accuracy_scores), 4),
        "std_accuracy": round(np.std(accuracy_scores), 4),
        "mean_precision": round(np.mean(precision_scores), 4),
        "mean_recall": round(np.mean(recall_scores), 4),
        "mean_f1": round(np.mean(f1_scores), 4),
        "mean_confusion_matrix": cm_df,
        "train_loss_list": train_losses,
        "val_loss_list": val_losses,
    }

def smooth(values, window=5):
    return np.convolve(values, np.ones(window)/window, mode='valid')

models_with_loss = {
    name: result for name, result in results_dict.items()
    if name != "KNN" and result.get("train_loss_list") is not None and not all(np.isnan(result["train_loss_list"]))
}

n_models = len(models_with_loss)
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, n_models, figsize=(5 * n_models, 4), sharey=True)

if n_models == 1:
    axes = [axes]


y_min = 0
y_max = max(
    max(np.nanmax(r["val_loss_list"]) if r["val_loss_list"] else 0 for r in models_with_loss.values()),
    max(np.nanmax(r["train_loss_list"]) if r["train_loss_list"] else 0 for r in models_with_loss.values())
)
y_max = min(y_max * 1.1, 4)


for ax, (name, result) in zip(axes, models_with_loss.items()):
    train = result["train_loss_list"]
    val = result["val_loss_list"]

    train_smooth = smooth(train)
    val_smooth = smooth(val)

    ax.plot(train_smooth, label="Train", color="steelblue", linewidth=2)
    ax.plot(val_smooth, label="Validation", color="tomato", linestyle="--", linewidth=2)

    min_index = np.argmin(val_smooth)
    min_val = val_smooth[min_index]
    ax.axvline(min_index, color="gray", linestyle=":", alpha=0.6)
    ax.annotate(f"Min\n{min_val:.2f}", xy=(min_index, min_val),
                xytext=(min_index + 5, min_val + 0.1),
                arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", color="gray"),
                fontsize=9, color="gray")

    ax.set_title(name)
    ax.set_xlabel("Bootstrap Iteration")
    ax.set_ylim(y_min, y_max)
    ax.grid(True)
    ax.legend()
    if ax == axes[0]:
        ax.set_ylabel("Loss")

plt.suptitle("Train vs Validation Log Loss", fontsize=16)
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])
plt.show()

This result makes sense because bootstrapping reduces variance by averaging over multiple resampled training sets, leading to stable and consistent performance across iterations. The small gap between train and validation loss reflects the model's ability to generalize well, as each iteration evaluates on slightly different data.

Conclusion: SVM achieved the highest mean accuracy (0.7986) and the best F1 score (0.7181), making it the strongest overall performer in terms of both precision and balance. While LDA showed relatively high accuracy (0.7882) and precision (0.7610), its lower recall (0.6504) indicates it misses more actual survivors. This is also shown in NBC and KNN, which have higher recall than LDA but lower F1 scores overall.

Section 12: Hyperparameter Tuning - Model Tuned Performance¶

After getting the baselines, let's see if we can improve on the indivdual model results. We will use mostly grid search to tune the model and also randomized search for efficiency.

In [46]:
def clf_performance(classifier, model_name, X_val, y_val):
    y_pred = classifier.predict(X_val)
    print(f"Model: {model_name}")
    print(f"Best Score: {classifier.best_score_:.4f}")
    print(f"Best Parameters: {classifier.best_params_}")
    print("Validation Metrics:")
    print(f"   - Accuracy : {accuracy_score(y_val, y_pred):.4f}")
    print(f"   - Precision: {precision_score(y_val, y_pred):.4f}")
    print(f"   - Recall   : {recall_score(y_val, y_pred):.4f}")
    print(f"   - F1 Score : {f1_score(y_val, y_pred):.4f}")

Section 16 : Summary¶

In this project, we aimed to classify Titanic passengers into survivors and non-survivors. We trained and evaluated several classification models: KNN, LDA, NBC, and SVM, and validated them using bootstrapping. We also performed feature selection using backward and hybrid strategies. Each model was evaluated with KPI metrics.

What Worked Well: Feature engineering significantly improved performance, also Bootstrapping allowed us to evaluate model stability over multiple resamplings.

What Did'nt Work So Well: It was difficult to find one model that excelled in all performance metrics.
